				\begin{document}$$\left [ {\frac{{{\rm \%\, Diet \,DM} - ( {\frac{{\rm \%\, Fecal \,DM \; \times \% \,Diet \,Ti}}{{\rm \% \,Fecal \,Ti}}} )}}{{\rm \% \,Diet \,DM}}}\right ]\; \times \;100,$$\end{document}%DietDM-(%FecalDM×%DietTi%FecalTi)%DietDM×100,where DM is dry matter and Ti is titanium dioxide. Dry matter digestibility was log-transformed to obtain a normal distribution of the data and the transformed data was used for all downstream analyses.

GWAS for phenotypic traits with SNP genotypes was done using GenSel software [17]. Bayes B, which fits all SNPs simultaneously as random effects, was used for the analysis. The following mixed model was used for the GWAS:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathbf{y = Xb}}{ + }\sum\limits_{\text{j}}^{\text{k}} {{\mathbf{z}}_{\text{j}} \upalpha_{\text{j}} \delta_{\text{j}} { + } {\upvarepsilon} },$$\end{document}y=Xb+∑jkzjαjδj+ε, where y is a vector of phenotypes, X is an incidence matrix to account for fixed effects on phenotypes, b is a vector of fixed effects, zj is a vector of genotypes for SNP j based on the number of B alleles (−10, 0, +10, or the average of the genotypes at SNP j), αj is the allele substitution effect for SNP j, δj is a parameter that indicates whether SNP j was included in the Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) chain, and ε is the error associated with the analysis. For one analysis per trait, a total of 41,000 MCMC iterations were completed and the first 1000 iterations were discarded.
